          "assignments": [
            {
              "id": "31d6c122-85e0-45e2-b520-0e73181b4b38",
              "name": "Script",
              "value": "Bitcoin was created in 2009 by an anonymous person or group known as Satoshi Nakamoto. It was the first decentralized digital currency, operating without a central bank or single administrator. Transactions are verified by network nodes through cryptography and recorded on a public ledger called the blockchain. Each block contains a hash of the previous block, forming an unbreakable chain of records. New bitcoins are created through a process called mining, where powerful computers solve complex mathematical puzzles. The total supply of Bitcoin is capped at 21 million coins, making it a deflationary asset by design. Bitcoin can be divided into smaller units called satoshis, with one satoshi equaling one hundred millionth of a single bitcoin. Over the years, Bitcoin has evolved from a niche internet experiment into a globally recognized store of value. Major companies and institutional investors have added Bitcoin to their balance sheets as a hedge against inflation. El Salvador became the first country to adopt Bitcoin as legal tender in 2021. The Bitcoin network processes transactions without intermediaries, enabling peer-to-peer transfers across borders. Its price has experienced dramatic volatility, reaching all-time highs and sharp corrections throughout its history. Despite criticism over energy consumption, many mining operations have shifted toward renewable energy sources. Bitcoin's decentralized nature means no single entity can control or shut down the network. It remains the largest cryptocurrency by market capitalization and continues to shape the future of digital finance.",
              "type": "string"
            }
          ]
        },
        "options": {}
